				<p>Today, thanks to the uber connectedness of the internet, and social media, we now have an average of 500 people in our "address books"--most of whom we barely talk to in any given year.  Even worse: when you add up all the contacts in our phones, social media, and email inboxes, we all have an average of over 3000 contacts. Whoah!</p>
				<p>How the heck to truly stay in touch with this many people?  Answer: you don't.  It is virtually impossible to stay in touch with this many people given the way we currently manage our contacts.</p>
				<p>Enter Contact Points.  A new type of contact management software.</p>
				<p>Most contact management software focuses simply on when you last contacted someone.  But that's irrelevant.  What matters most is the <em>quality</em> of your interactions with your contacts.  How to track that?  We do so for you via points.  Every interaction logged assigns a point value based on many different variables that measure the quality of the interaction.  The more you use it, the more easily the algorithm tells you who you should be contacting next to keep your relationships strong.  Just do what it says, and you'll never again say, "Oh my gosh, has it really been that long since we've seen talked!"</p>
